<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>I don't see it as social media, more an information and discussion page/site. The concept I was more aiming for is that Foundation employees are expected to be mature and reasonable enough to interact with civilians appropriately, and that extends to online. There's also no <em>obligation to post there,</em> and I'm sure that's why very few Foundation personnel actually posted in it, and none of them argued with civilians unless to clarify a fact. While I can see the reasoning behind saying they wouldn't have this system at all, if they do have it, I don't see why it can't function somewhat professionally. Anyone whose job is to protect society should at least be able to interact with society online in a levelheaded manner. If they don't, there are moderators on IntSCPFN watching their behavior and reporting it to supervisors if necessary. It's not a place where you can just say whatever without consequence, and personnel know that.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>hmm i wonder what real life situation this might be an allegory for???</p>
</blockquote>
<p>It's not anything specific, at least that I intended. If you mean &quot;is it supposed to look like 4chan boards,&quot; it's not what crossed my mind while I was writing but I can see the connection because of having anons and a simple text format. If you mean the issues the skip is addressing, this one wasn't inspired by real-world issues other than politics (and voting season) in general, unlike two other tales for this canon that you might be referencing. The specific issue of containing humans isn't allegory for anything in this case.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>I'm glad that you liked it despite the issues, though!</p>
<p>Edit: I agree that Rogers was toeing the behavior line and not a good example. I changed his comment and Trauss' reply accordingly.</p>

							</div>

								
